The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Corporate Briefs

 Hospitality firm Asian Hotels is planning to raise up to Rs 180 crore through an issue of non-convertible preference shares. The company on April 30 had proposed to raise Rs 90 crore through redeemable non-convertible preference shares. However, it suspended the plan. The was because of a notification from the finance ministry which said foreign investment through optionally convertible preference shares would be considered as debt and would require compliance with the guidelines on external commercial borrowings.

 Larsen amp; Toubro Limited (L amp;T) has secured an order valued at Rs. 215 crore from the Abu Dhabi Water amp; Electricity Authority for the supply and installation of 33-kv power cables and fibre optic cables for inter connections between various substations in the eastern region of Abu Dhabi.

 The board of Pune-based Autoline Industries has recommended Rs 2 per share as final dividend (20 per cent) on equity shares of Rs 10 each (par value) for the financial year ended March 31.The automobile ancillary maker told the bse that the dividend pay-out is subject to the approval of the shareholders.

 Bosch Chassis Systems India, a subsidiary of Germany-based Bosch Group, has announced a bonus issue in the ratio of 1:1. The issue will increase the companys paid-up share capital to Rs 20.79 crore from Rs 10.39 crore. Company chairman Peter Delhey said the accounting period ended December 31, 2006 was a truncated one of nine months as the firm will facilitate consolidation of results with the Bosch Group at the global level.

 Tata Consultancy Services has launched its UK Innovation Lab in Peterborough. The lab will provide customers with an experience centre where new domain solutions can be developed, incubated and piloted. 

 Syschem Indias board of directors has approved consolidation (reverse stock-split) of 10 equity shares of Re 1 into one equity share of Rs 10 each.An extra ordinary general meeting will be held on May 29 to get the shareholders approval, Syschem informed the bse

 MaxiMaa Systems has earmarked a capital expenditure of about Rs 60 crore over the next two years. The company plans to expand its manufacturing capacities and also its steel furniture and storage systems categories.

 Tata Indicom has launched Huwaei C5300 for its postpaid subscribers. It is a digital camera phone and is priced at Rs 3,999. It has a FM Radio and an MP3.

